1 Overview and Motivation

Increases in real estate prices were seen across the country over the course of the COVID-19 pandemic, with the Case-Shiller U.S. National Home Price Index showing an 18.6% growth in housing prices over the course of September 2020 to 2021. Some factors contributing to this trend included both COVID-related and unrelated factors, such as: lower lending interest rates, changes in migration from urban to suburban areas or smaller cities given an increase in remote working, millennials aging into homeownership, an increase in second-home buying, and a variety of other factors.

We wanted to examine how the real estate prices in and around Boston were affected in the years before and after the start of the COVID-19 pandemic defined as March 2020 when Mayor Marty Walsh decladed a public health emergency. Given that Boston is a huge healthcare hub with some of the leading hospitals, pharmaceutical, and biotech companies, its housing market is more likely to be impacted by COVID-19 trends than other cities. Thus, it is a good model city to study the pandemic-related factors affecting housing inflation. Furthermore, given that Boston has the 4th most number of colleges in the US, trends in housing markets during the COVID-19 pandemic were likely to be affected by the remote learning of 2020 and 2021 influx of college and graduate students as schools moved toward hybrid models of remote and in-person learning.

In addition to the effect of the pandemic, we also wanted to explore other factors that may have affected the property prices. We want to contrast how price inflation varies according to neighbourhoods and differences in neighborhood area deprivation index (ADI), school ratings, air quality index (AQI), etc. if available. Thus, we will begin to understand the local trends in housing prices in Boston before and after the start of the COVID-19 pandemic and begin to explore COVID-related and unrelated factors that could have influenced these trends.

2 Related work

We were in part inspired by this article on national housing trends during the COVID-19 pandemic that was released by the White House.

3 Initial questions

Our initial plan was the following:

  • Objective 1: To assess the actual house sale price trend in real estate units from 2017 to 2021, with special attention to the years of the COVID-19 pandemic (2020-2021) and compare this to property value assessment data available from the Analyze Boston website (https://data.boston.gov/). We plan to look at the actual selling price of various units from different Boston neighborhoods through a real estate database (i.e., Zillow, Redfin, or Trulia) and compare it to the City of Boston home assessment prices to see the divergence in the values that could be attributable to property price inflation.

  • Objective 2: Utilizing regression models based on property data from pre-pandemic (2017-2019) and pandemic (2020-2021) years, we will predict the possible change in housing prices for different metropolitan and suburban regions of Boston in 2022 given 1) there is no further COVID-19 surge and 2) there is another COVID-19 surge.

  • Objective 3: To assess for factors that affect inflation of property price beyond COVID-19, including sociodemographic (i.e., neighbourhood, ADI, facilities (i.e., proximity to medical center, school district ratings and environmental data (i.e., AQI).

4 Data sources

  1. Primary data regarding the actual housing values was defined as government assessment values and obtained through the city of Boston property assessment database for the years of 2017-2021.

  2. Real world property closing price data was obtained through web scraping from publicly available property listing websites including:

  • For pre-COVID housing sale data from 2015-2019, average housing sale prices stratified by metropolitan Boston neighborhoods were obtained from Boston Magazine.
    • Years 2015-2016
    • Years 2017-2018
    • Years 2018-2019
  • For post-COVID housing sale data from 2020, average housing sale price stratified by neighborhood was obtained from Redfin.
  • For post-COVID housing sale data from 2021, housing sale prices from the 5 most recent properties in each metro Boston Neighborhood was individually scrapped from Redfin.
  1. We opted to include a few additional factors contributing to housing prices. The Air Quality Index (AQI) scores were obtained from this website. The Area Deprivation Index (ADI), which are scores of disadvantaged neighborhoods that can have important effects on healthcare outcomes, were obtained from this website.

5 Adjustment in Analyses

Pre-analysis Planning Adjustments

After discussion with our TA, Rolando, we refined our questions to:

Can we use data from 2017-2019 to predict housing prices in 2020?

  • Step 1: Build a training and test set from 2017-2019

  • Step 2: Optimize model

  • Step 3: Apply to predict prices in 2020-2021.

Post-web scraping/data uploading Adjustments

The initial plan was to scrape individual housing sale data from each year and to match the property with the governement assessments data but adjustments were made after encountering obstacles in data scraping and merging of the primary data.

  • Historic hosuing sale data (i.e., for 2015-2020) at the individual property level is not available on webistes such as Redfin, Zillow, and Trulia

  • Historic sale price data was only avaialble as an average for city or neighborhoods within the city

  • Average property assessment value by neighborhood for 2015-2020 were used since there was not individual property sale data available for those years

  • Sale prices from 2021 would have to be scraped for each individual property and since our coding skills were not advanced enough to automate this process, it limited data collection to 5 properties from each of the approximately 20 Boston neighborhoods

  • Linking of the 2021 assessments data and the actual housing sale data proved extremely difficult because there was not a unifying ID, therefore average property assessment value by neighborhoods was used

Analysis Adjustments

The final dataset was extremely large but there was significant missingness for several covariables. To account for this and to prevent maxing out on R memory, the analysis was restricted to data from 2017-2021 although 2015 and 2016 housing sale data had been found.

We also found that many of our planned potential predictors ended up having no effect on the models and were only slowing down our RMD file (in some cases, preventing the file from knitting completely). Thus, those factors were removed. However, we left the code for uploading and data wrangling for those factors in this RMD (without running it) to show our thought process.

6.2.2 Data wrangling

We filtered out the properties that were only residential (“A”, “CD”, “CM”, “R1”, “R2”, “R3”, “R4”, “RC”, which stand for “Residential 7 or more units”, “Residential condominium unit”, “Condominium main”, “Residential 1-family,” “2-family”, “3-family”, “4- or more family”, and “Mixed use (residential and commercial)”).

The data was not always formatted the same way per year, so the data wrangling allowed us to clean up names and classes of variables, limit data to residential property only, and select for variables of interest. Additionally, data from the same variable (ie. number of bedrooms) was often placed in two different columns depending on whether they were a residential unit (“r”) or a condo unit (“u”), so they were combined into a single variable.

We chose to use select for the following variables given that they are often the variables of greatest importance when initially choosing a home:

  • Zipcode, neighborhood, street address

  • Assessed value (land, building, total) – as this plays into the cost of the home

  • Tax – another proxy for the value of the home

  • Square feet of land/property

  • Number of bedrooms and bathrooms

  • Year built/remodeled

  • Additional variables were included for consideration: overall condition, AC and heating type, number of floors.

  • Other variables were available but had a large amount of missingness or seemed trivial compared to other variables in determining property value.

eval2017 <- eval2017 %>% 
  filter(lu %in% c("A", "CD", "CM", "R1", "R2", "R3", "R4", "RC")) %>% # Lu refers to type of property; limiting data to residential property only
  mutate(st_name = paste(st_name, st_name_suf)) %>%  #Match format of addresses to those in 2021 dataset
  mutate(ac_type = ifelse(!is.na(r_ac), r_ac, u_ac)) %>% # Different variables used for residential properties (r) and units (u), so this is code to unify them into one variable
  mutate(heat_type = ifelse(!is.na(r_heat_typ), r_heat_typ, u_heat_typ)) %>% 
  mutate(heat_type = replace(heat_type, heat_type == "C", NA), #Removing heat types not in codebook
         heat_type = replace(heat_type, heat_type == "D", NA), 
         heat_type = replace(heat_type, heat_type == "f", NA), 
         heat_type = replace(heat_type, heat_type == "G", NA), 
         heat_type = replace(heat_type, heat_type == "I", NA), 
         heat_type = replace(heat_type, heat_type == "Y", NA)) %>% 
  mutate(bedrooms = ifelse(!is.na(r_bdrms), r_bdrms, u_bdrms)) %>% 
  mutate(bath_full = ifelse(!is.na(r_full_bth), r_full_bth, u_full_bth)) %>% 
  mutate(bath_half = ifelse(!is.na(r_half_bth), r_half_bth, u_half_bth)) %>% 
  rename(condition = r_ovrall_cnd) %>% 
  mutate(pid = str_sub(pid, 1, 10)) %>% #String processing to reformat number IDs
  mutate(zipcode = as.character(str_sub(zipcode, 1, 5))) %>% #changing zipcode to character without dash at the end
  mutate(gross_tax=gross_tax/100)%>%#Correcting a mistake in original CSV
  select(pid, zipcode, st_name, lu, av_bldg, av_land, av_total, st_name, gross_tax, land_sf, living_area, num_floors, ac_type, heat_type, bedrooms, bath_full, bath_half, condition, yr_built, yr_remod) %>%  #Keeping assessed value for the building, land, and total. Keeping address (st_name) and parcel numbers for reference (pid). Keeping tax bill amount (based on av_total and tax rate), square footage of land and living area. Keeping type of property. Keeping property-level factors: number of floors, presence of AC and heat (types), number of bedrooms, number of full and half bathrooms, overall condition, year built, year remodeled
  mutate(year = 2017) #Creating a year variable for year of assessment

6.3 Air Quality Index (AQI)

This ended up being a predictor that we did not use in our final models. Thus, we did not run the code in the final models but included it below to demonstrate our thought process and work.

Reading in AQI data:

Note: We had air quality data for four Boston-area neighborhoods. The data was originally in the form of PM2.5 (Parameter name PM2.5 local conditions), which were subsequently converted to AQI by this table. Given we didn’t have all the data to use the AQI calculation and derive exact numbers, we instead made AQI a factor variable with 5 levels using the following table (reference 1, reference 2):

aqi_boston <- clean_names(read_csv("boston-air-quality.csv")) %>% 
  mutate(date = ymd(date)) %>% 
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year(date))) %>% 
  filter(year %in% c(2017, 2018, 2019, 2020, 2021)) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(pm25_mean = mean(pm25, na.rm = T),
           aqi = case_when(pm25_mean <= 15.5 ~ 51, 
                         pm25_mean > 15.5 & pm25_mean <= 40.5 ~ 101, 
                         pm25_mean > 40.5 & pm25_mean <= 65.5 ~ 151,
                         pm25_mean > 65.5 & pm25_mean <= 150.5 ~ 201, 
                         TRUE ~ 251)) %>% 
  mutate(neighborhood = "Downtown")

aqi_north_end <- clean_names(read_csv("boston-north end-air-quality.csv")) %>%

  mutate(year = as.numeric(year(date))) %>%

           aqi = case_when(pm25_mean <= 15.5 ~ 51, 
                         pm25_mean > 15.5 & pm25_mean <= 40.5 ~ 101, 
                         pm25_mean > 40.5 & pm25_mean <= 65.5 ~ 151,

6.4 Area Deprivation Index (ADI)

This was another factor we did not use in our final model. One potential reason is that ADI was collinear with neighborhoods. Thus, we did not run the code in the final models but included it below to demonstrate our thought process and work.

Reading in ADI data from the Neighborhood Atlas website.

Note: Codebook as follows:

  • TYPE: P indicates post office; U indicates unique zipcode; standard zip codes are left blank

  • ZIPID: The 9 digit zip code ID

  • FIPS: The block group Census ID

  • GISJOIN: Key linkage field to the block group shapefile served by NHGIS

  • ADI_NATRANK: National percentile of block group ADI score. PH for suppression due to low population and/or housing, GQ for suppression due to a high group quarters population, and PH-GQ for suppression due to both types of suppression criteria.

  • ADI_STATERNK: State-specific decile of block group ADI score. PH for suppression due to low population and/or housing, GQ for suppression due to a high group quarters population, and PH-GQ for suppression due to both types of suppression criteria.

Given that we had ADI data available for 2015 and 2019 only, for analysis purposes, the assumption was made that 2015 is comparable enough to 2017, when our analysis begins; thus 2015 was used as a proxy for 2017.

#Defining a function for mode
getmode <- function(v) {
  uniqv <- unique(v)
   uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

adi2019 <- clean_names(read.delim('MA_2019_ADI_9 Digit Zip Code_v3.1.txt', sep = ",")) %>%

Create function to string proccess scraped data. Final output is datatable.

redfin.fun <- function(x) {
  x %>% str_split_fixed(pattern = "\\%", n=5) %>%
    str_replace_all("[^[:alnum:]]","") %>% 
    str_replace_all(c("KSalePrice\\d*"="000",
                    "MSalePrice\\d*"="000000",
                    "sincelastyear"="", 
                    "SaleSqFt\\d*"="",
                    "TotalHomesSold"="",
                    "K"="0"))
}

6.5.3 Data wrangling

Combining all of the dataframes for 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019, 2020.

Datatable information: This table includes aggregate data from all neighborhoods of Boston. The 2015-2019 data is from Boston Magazine and the associated pages of each year. The 2020 data is from Redfin and the associated individual neighborhood pages.

Description of data within columns: * Neighborhood - factor w 27 levels; includes all neighborhoods of Boston (Allston, Back Bay, Bay Village South End, Beacon Hill, Brighton, Charlestown, Chestnut Hill, Chinatown Leather District, Dorchester, Downtown, East Boston, Fenway, Hyde Park, Jamaica Plain, Mattapan, North End West End, Roslindale, Roxbury, Seaport District, South Boston, West Roxbury, Citywide). Of note, data is only available for Seaport District and Downtown, and Chestnut Hill in Redfin. Data is only available for Citywide in Boston Magazine. Brookline, Cambridge, and Somerville were included as neighborhoods of interest althought they are not considered to be in Boston. The row for Boston is a composite measurement that is included in both Redfin and some of the Boston Magazine data. * Year - number * Avg Sale Price - number; median price was used for Boston Magazine, unclear which measurement was used to calculate the average sale price listed by Redfin. * Price Per SqFt - number; only available for Redfin data. * Number Sold - number; units sold in that neighborhood, missing from Boston Magazine 2017 data. * Type - character; Boston Magazine data was stratified by condo verses single family housing units. In the 2015 and 2016 data both condo and single family housing data was available for the neighborhoods of Boston and Brookline, Cambridge, Somerville. Subsequent years condo data is only availble for the neighborhoods of Boston while housing data is only for Brookline, Cambridge, Somerville, and the composite Boston category.

df.bos.housing <-rbind(df.boston, l_condo_sixteen, l_house_sixteen, l_condo_nineteen, l_house_nineteen, l_condo_twenty, l_house_twenty)
df.bos.housing <-df.bos.housing %>% arrange(Year)

df.bos.housing <- clean_names(df.bos.housing)

Since we don’t have City of Boston data for the years of 2015 and 2016, we opted to use them as a proxy for 2017. Thus, we changed the years to 2017 and took the mean average sale price after grouping by neighborhood, type, and year.

df.bos.housing <- df.bos.housing %>% 
  mutate(year = replace(year, year == 2015, 2017), 
         year = replace(year, year == 2016, 2017)) %>% 
  group_by(neighborhood, type, year) %>% 
  mutate(avg_sale_price = mean(avg_sale_price)) %>% 
  ungroup()

6.6 Cumulative data for analysis

Steps included:

  • Joining sales data scraped from Redfin and Boston magazine with the City of Boston data

  • Removed missing values from key variables (particularly outcome), making the assumption that missingness is random and additional bias would not be introduced.

  • Created a binary variable “COVID19” that was FALSE for years 2017-19 and TRUE for years 2020-21.

  • Created a binary variable “SALE” that was TRUE for high sale values, or above the median of average sale price, and FALSE for low sale values, or below the median of average sale price)

# Joining sales data scraped from Redfin and Boston magazine with the City of Boston data

full_long_new <- subset(full_long_new, select=-c(price_per_sq_ft, number_sold, pid, zipid, st_name, ac_type, heat_type, bath_full, bath_half, condition, year.y))

We also found at this point that we were using a lot of memory in the RStudio global environment. For some of us, the analysis below simply did not run (“Error: vector memory exhausted (limit reached?)”). To address this issue, we pursued two steps:

  1. Clearing dataframes and lists that are no longer needed in the rest of this R markdown.

  2. Taking a random sample of the cumulative data and using that for the rest of the analysis. This is certainly a limitation to our analysis, but we agreed that a random sample of 750,000 still gave us adequate power for our analysis. Of note, we also ran our models on the full data set (>9 million, called “full_data_new”), 25% of the data, and 750,000 observations of the data (“rando”). We did not include that code in this R markdown, and opted to show the models based on the sample size of 750,000 observations for consistent results, as we found that the larger samples would often prevent the file from knitting or running, or would exhaust the vector memory. We’ve included some commentary on our analysis run on the full data or 25% of the data, as applicable.

The context of COVID appeared to increase a home’s sale price as compared to pre-COVID times, neighborhood being held constant. For computation power and speed in this file we included a random draw. This said, the full data set with home sale price (“full_long_new”) increased $1,446,869 in the context of COVID with 95% confidence interval [1,435,742, 1,457,996], holding neighborhood constant (analysis not shown). In the random ~10% sample (“rando”) with wider 95% CI, the effect estimate is an increased home sale price of $1,438,942 increase [1,399,017, 1,478,867], holding neighborhood constant. We noted here that the 10% sample is a reasonable proxy for the full data frame. We will utilize the random sample to fit a logistic regression model with a training and test set later. For now, we should examine the years (each of 2020 and 2021) for a more nuanced picture as below.

To allow for a bit finer resolution and taking into account the visualizations above that appear to show a return back down in homes’ sale prices in 2021, we regressed neighborhood and year as factors for the outcome of average sale price of a home. This allowed for rough estimation of the factor of 2020, as compared to 2017, and then of 2021 as compared to 2017 (and indirectly to 2020), assuming the same neighborhood.

9 GLM model

We moved on to take advantage of our recently created binary variable “SALE” (explained above in 6.6 Cumulative data for analysis) to fit a GLM model. Given the large number of observations, we had the luxury of using 70% of our data to train and 30% to test for the outcome of high vs low expected sale price. The overall accuracy for a given random sample ranges in the 70s%, sensitivity of 90s% and specificity of 30-40s%.

set.seed(1)
index_train<- createDataPartition(y = rando$SALE, times =1, p=0.7, list = FALSE)
train_set <- slice(rando, index_train)
test_set <- slice(rando, -index_train)
glm_fit <- train_set %>% mutate(y=as.numeric(SALE =="1")) %>% glm(SALE~neighborhood+as.factor(year.x), data=., family="binomial")
p_hat_logit <- predict(glm_fit, newdata = test_set, type="response")
y_hat_logit <- ifelse(p_hat_logit > 0.5, "1", "0")
confusionMatrix(data = as.factor(y_hat_logit), reference = test_set$SALE)
